 for regularization [Data: Entities (69); Relationships (127)]. The loss function used was Cross Entropy Loss from PyTorch [Data: Entities (358); Relationships (619)]. Training utilized mini-batch gradient descent with a batch size of around 16, balancing computational efficiency and convergence stability [Data: Entities (377); Relationships (651)]. Performance was tracked across epochs using separate training and validation sets, with reported batch losses around 4.5 [Data: Entities (385, 382, 383, 388); Relationships (666, 668, 669, 670)]. This configuration reflects standard practices in deep learning while being tailored to the complexities of scientific text summarization.\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Preprocessing pipelines are essential to handle linguistic and structural variability\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Due to the heterogeneous nature of the CORD-19 dataset, a robust preprocessing pipeline was necessary. This included the PYTHON LIBRARY LANGDETECT to filter non-English papers, ensuring linguistic consistency [Data: Entities (365)]. The COTO TOKENIZER, a word-based tokenization tool governed by regex rules, was used to convert raw text into discrete tokens suitable for model input, with special handling for out-of-vocabulary terms and symbols [Data: Entities (368); Relationships (641, 645)]. Figures 11 and 13 illustrate the data distribution and tokenizer rules, respectively, underscoring the importance of structured preprocessing [Data: Entities (371, 373); Relationships (685, 645)]. Without these steps, the model would struggle with the dataset’s inherent noise and variability, as acknowledged in the thesis’s discussion of data preparation challenges [Data: Entities (263, 457)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Ethical considerations around researcher attribution are explicitly addressed\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The author of the thesis explicitly acknowledges the ethical issue of using ope